{"title_page": "Joyce Irby", "text_new": "{{short description|American musician}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{mi|\n{{BLP sources|date=July 2008}}\n}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name            = Joyce \"Fenderella\" Irby\n| image           =\n| caption         =\n| image_size      =\n| background      = solo_singer\n| birth_name      = Joyce Irby\n| alias           = Fenderella\n|\n| death_date      =\n| origin          = [[Fort Bragg, NC]]/[[Eatonville, FL]], [[United States|U.S.]] <br> [[Los Angeles, California|Los Angeles]], [[California]], [[United States|U.S.]]\n| instrument      = [[Human voice|Vocals]], [[piano]], [[bass guitar]]\n| genre           = [[R&B]], [[Soul music|soul]], [[jazz-funk]], [[pop music|pop]], [[smooth soul]]\n| occupation      = Singer, songwriter, musician, record producer, artist developer\n| years_active    = 1970s\u2013present\n| label           = [[Motown Records]]<br>[[MCA Records]] \n| associated_acts = [[George Clinton (funk musician)|George Clinton]]<br>[[Klymaxx]]<br> [[Sammie|Sammie Bush]]<br>[[Lloyd (singer)|Lloyd (The Inc)]] <br>[[N-Toon]]<br> Angel Diaz\n| website         = www.jamsforanimals.org\n}}\n\n'''Joyce \"Fenderella\" Irby'''  is an American-born singer and songwriter, [[bassist]], and a artist developer. She was the co-lead vocalist of the 1980s [[all-female band]] [[Klymaxx]].<ref name=\"Huey\">{{cite web|url={{Allmusic|class=artist|id=p4695|pure_url=yes}}|title=Biography: Klymaxx|last=Huey|first=Steve|publisher=[[Allmusic]]|accessdate=1 August 2010}}</ref> She has produced a top 5 record, \"Mr. D.J.\" and her Motown album, \"Maximum Thrust,\u201d features three charted singles. She is also the founder of Diva One Productions, Inc.  \n\n==Career==\nIrby in her teenage years, used to stand outside concert arenas in the south with her bass around her neck, playing on the loading ramp. There she was first noticed by George Clinton. He used to maker her sit with him after concerts, encouraged her by listening to her play. \n\n=== Solo Artist ===\nShe originally signed on with [[George Clinton (funk musician)|George Clinton]]'s P-Funk crew as \"Fenderella\". In 1989, she scored a solo deal with [[Motown Records]] and had 3 charted Billboard singles, most notable \"Mr. DJ\" with [[Doug E. Fresh]] which peaked at #2.\n\nIrby relocated from Los Angeles to [[Atlanta]] in the late 1980s and since 1986 began attempting to engineer the rise of Atlanta as an urban music center by soliciting major record labels and producers [[Jimmy Jam and Terry Lewis]], and [[L.A. Reid]] & [[Babyface (musician)|Babyface]] to form regional offices in the Atlanta area.\n\n=== Klymaxx ===\nDick Griffey, president of Solar Records, saw Irby perform at Loading Ramp and he asked Leon Sylvers, the producer, if he could contact her. They were in search of a female bass player for their new group Klymaxx. \n\nJimmy Jam heard her singing while he was playing piano in the studio with the girls which led her to the opportunity to lead Klymaxx songs. She was the lead singer on 3 of Klymaxx\u2019s 4 biggest records, including their biggest hit \u201cI Miss You.\u201d She also penned and recorded the group\u2019s first hit, \u201cThe Men All Pause.\"\n\n=== Diva One Productions ===\nIrby relocated to Atlanta where she founded Diva One Productions,a  production and publishing company. She signed a 16-year-old writer/producer, Dallas Austin. Her greater impact may have been the result of her signing a young [[Dallas Austin]] as a songwriter and producer in 1988. Dallas produced the first [[TLC (band)|TLC]] and [[Boyz II Men]] projects while still signed to Irby's company Diva One Entertainment.\n\nAs an artist developer she signed child star [[Sammie|Sammie Bush]], and made a deal with Dallas and [[Capitol Records]] which launched Sammie's career when he was 12 years old. Irby also signed [[Lloyd (singer)|Lloyd (The Inc)]] as an 11-year-old and developed and guided his career through four major record deals (Warner, DreamWorks, Magic Johnson Music/MCA, The Inc/Universal). Irby gave multi platinum writer/producer Jasper Cameron his first songwriting deal. In 2012 Irby scored a top 5 Billboard hit as a co-writer with the [[Fat Joe]]/[[Chris Brown]] song, \"Another Round\".\n\nJoyce had early success as a writer/producer with Klymaxx, Shalamar, The Boys, Braxtons, Ricca, Sammie, Lloyd, and Carrie Lucas & Troop.\n\n=== Honors and awards ===\nIrby won an ASCAP songwriter award in 2012 for co-penning one of the most played Urban records in the US, a top 5 single, \u201cAnother Round\u201d, by Fat Joe, Chris Brown, & Mary J Blige. \n\n==Personal life==\nAn avid animal lover, Irby started her own [[Charitable organization|charity]] \"Jams For Animals\", to raise consciousness and promote kindness to animals through music and video.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20100709215538/http://klymaxx.outofprintsoulandfunk.com/ Klymaxx @ T-Mad's Music]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Irby, Joyce}}\n[[Category:American bass guitarists]]\n[[Category:Female bass guitarists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1954 births]]\n[[Category:People from Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:People from Fort Bragg, North Carolina]]\n[[Category:African-American female singers]]\n[[Category:American female singers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American bass guitarists]]\n[[Category:People from Eatonville, Florida]]\n[[Category:20th-century American women musicians]]\n\n\n{{US-bass-guitarist-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American musician}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{mi|\n{{BLP sources|date=July 2008}}\n}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name            = Joyce \"Fenderella\" Irby\n| image           =\n| caption         =\n| image_size      =\n| background      = solo_singer\n| birth_name      = Joyce Irby\n| alias           = Fenderella\n|\n| death_date      =\n| origin          = [[Fort Bragg, NC]]/[[Eatonville, FL]], [[United States|U.S.]] <br> [[Los Angeles, California|Los Angeles]], [[California]], [[United States|U.S.]]\n| instrument      = [[Human voice|Vocals]], [[piano]], [[bass guitar]]\n| genre           = [[R&B]], [[Soul music|soul]], [[jazz-funk]], [[pop music|pop]], [[smooth soul]]\n| occupation      = Singer, songwriter, musician, record producer, artist developer\n| years_active    = 1970s\u2013present\n| label           = [[Motown Records]]<br>[[MCA Records]] \n| associated_acts = [[George Clinton (funk musician)|George Clinton]]<br>[[Klymaxx]]<br> [[Sammie|Sammie Bush]]<br>[[Lloyd (singer)|Lloyd (The Inc)]] <br>[[N-Toon]]<br> Angel Diaz\n| website         = www.jamsforanimals.org\n}}\n\n'''Joyce \"Fenderella\" Irby'''  is an American-born singer and songwriter, [[bassist]], and a artist developer. She was the co-lead vocalist of the 1980s [[all-female band]] [[Klymaxx]].<ref name=\"Huey\">{{cite web|url={{Allmusic|class=artist|id=p4695|pure_url=yes}}|title=Biography: Klymaxx|last=Huey|first=Steve|publisher=[[Allmusic]]|accessdate=1 August 2010}}</ref> She has produced a top 5 record, \"Mr. D.J.\" and her Motown album, \"Maximum Thrust,\u201d features three charted singles. She is also the founder of Diva One Productions, Inc.  \n\n==Career==\nIrby in her teenage years, used to stand outside concert arenas in the south with her bass around her neck, playing on the loading ramp. There she was first noticed by George Clinton. He used to maker her sit with him after concerts, encouraged her by listening to her play. \n\n=== Solo Artist ===\nShe originally signed on with [[George Clinton (funk musician)|George Clinton]]'s P-Funk crew as \"Fenderella\". In 1989, she scored a solo deal with [[Motown Records]] and had 3 charted Billboard singles, most notable \"Mr. DJ\" with [[Doug E. Fresh]] which peaked at #2.\n\nIrby relocated from Los Angeles to [[Atlanta]] in the late 1980s and since 1986 began attempting to engineer the rise of Atlanta as an urban music center by soliciting major record labels and producers [[Jimmy Jam and Terry Lewis]], and [[L.A. Reid]] & [[Babyface (musician)|Babyface]] to form regional offices in the Atlanta area.\n\n=== Klymaxx ===\nDick Griffey, president of Solar Records, saw Irby perform at Loading Ramp and he asked Leon Sylvers, the producer, if he could contact her. They were in search of a female bass player for their new group Klymaxx. \n\nJimmy Jam heard her singing while he was playing piano in the studio with the girls which led her to the opportunity to lead Klymaxx songs. She was the the lead singer on 3 of Klymaxx\u2019s 4 biggest records, including their biggest hit \u201cI Miss You.\u201d She also penned and recorded the group\u2019s first hit, \u201cThe Men All Pause.\"\n\n=== Diva One Productions ===\nIrby relocated to Atlanta where she founded Diva One Productions,a  production and publishing company. She signed a 16-year-old writer/producer, Dallas Austin. Her greater impact may have been the result of her signing a young [[Dallas Austin]] as a songwriter and producer in 1988. Dallas produced the first [[TLC (band)|TLC]] and [[Boyz II Men]] projects while still signed to Irby's company Diva One Entertainment.\n\nAs an artist developer she signed child star [[Sammie|Sammie Bush]], and made a deal with Dallas and [[Capitol Records]] which launched Sammie's career when he was 12 years old. Irby also signed [[Lloyd (singer)|Lloyd (The Inc)]] as an 11-year-old and developed and guided his career through four major record deals (Warner, DreamWorks, Magic Johnson Music/MCA, The Inc/Universal). Irby gave multi platinum writer/producer Jasper Cameron his first songwriting deal. In 2012 Irby scored a top 5 Billboard hit as a co-writer with the [[Fat Joe]]/[[Chris Brown]] song, \"Another Round\".\n\nJoyce had early success as a writer/producer with Klymaxx, Shalamar, The Boys, Braxtons, Ricca, Sammie, Lloyd, and Carrie Lucas & Troop.\n\n=== Honors and awards ===\nIrby won an ASCAP songwriter award in 2012 for co-penning one of the most played Urban records in the US, a top 5 single, \u201cAnother Round\u201d, by Fat Joe, Chris Brown, & Mary J Blige. \n\n==Personal life==\nAn avid animal lover, Irby started her own [[Charitable organization|charity]] \"Jams For Animals\", to raise consciousness and promote kindness to animals through music and video.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20100709215538/http://klymaxx.outofprintsoulandfunk.com/ Klymaxx @ T-Mad's Music]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Irby, Joyce}}\n[[Category:American bass guitarists]]\n[[Category:Female bass guitarists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1954 births]]\n[[Category:People from Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:People from Fort Bragg, North Carolina]]\n[[Category:African-American female singers]]\n[[Category:American female singers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American bass guitarists]]\n[[Category:People from Eatonville, Florida]]\n[[Category:20th-century American women musicians]]\n\n\n{{US-bass-guitarist-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Arjayay", "label": "safe", "comment": "Duplicate word removed", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Joyce_Irby"}
{"title_page": "Social House", "text_new": "{{short description|American pop duo}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Social House\n| image            = \n| landscape        = \n| caption          = \n| background       = group_or_band\n| alias            = \n| origin           = \n| genre            = <!--Please source genres -->[[Pop music|Pop]]<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.allmusic.com/artist/social-house-mn0003753155/biography|title=Social House Biography|website=[[AllMusic]]|last=Yeung|first=Neil|accessdate=October 15, 2019}}</ref>\n| years_active     = {{start date|2015\u2013present}}\n| label            = {{hlist|[[School Boy Records|School Boy]]|[[Republic Records|Republic]]}}\n| associated_acts  = [[Ariana Grande]]\n| website          = \n| current_members  = * Michael Foster\n* Charles Anderson\n| past_members     = \n}}\n\n'''Social House''' is an American musical duo from [[Pittsburgh]], [[Pennsylvania]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8471881/tbhits-producer-backstory-ariana-grande-songs-pete-davidson-goodnight-n-go-sweetener|title=Producer TBHits Reveals Backstory on 'Pete Davidson,' 'Goodnight n Go' From Grande of Araiana 'Sweetener'|website=Billboard|access-date=2019-01-25}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://the360mag.com/social-house-release-debut-single-magic-in-the-hamptons-ft-lil-yachty/|title=SOCIAL HOUSE RELEASE DEBUT SINGLE|last=wp360mag|date=2018-06-08|website=360 MAGAZINE {{!}} ART + MUSIC + DESIGN + FASHION + AUTO + TRAVEL + FOOD + HEALTH|language=en-US|access-date=2019-01-25}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.digitaljournal.com/entertainment/music/social-house-talks-new-track-magic-in-the-hamptons-and-drake/article/532430|title=Social House talks new track 'Magic In The Hamptons' and Drake (Includes interview)|date=2018-09-19|website=www.digitaljournal.com|access-date=2019-01-25}}</ref> As of 2019, the duo has released four singles.\n\n== History ==\nMichael \"Mikey\" Foster and Charles \"Scootie\" Anderson formed Social House in 2015 after moving to [[Los Angeles]] from [[Pittsburgh]].<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/events/women-in-music/8489187/social-house-interview-ariana-grande-tour|title=Social House Talk Writing Hits for J.Lo & Upcoming Tour With Ariana Grande|website=Billboard|access-date=2019-01-25}}</ref><ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://theknockturnal.com/exclusive-powerhouse-duo-social-house-are-pops-next-biggest-thing/|title=You are being redirected...|website=theknockturnal.com|access-date=2019-01-25}}</ref><ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://wild941.com/2018/08/07/nuthouse-sits-social-house/|title=The Nuthouse Sits Down With Social House|date=2018-08-07|website=WiLD 94.1|access-date=2019-01-25}}</ref> They worked in the same production studio<ref name=\":4\" /> and named themselves after the WiFi network of the house in which they lived.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.onestowatch.com/blog/new-artist-discovery-social-house-brings-their|title=NEW ARTIST DISCOVERY: Social House Brings Their Own Brand of Creative Magic to Hip-Hop / Ones To Watch|website=Ones To Watch|access-date=2019-01-25}}</ref><ref name=\":7\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.thenewpulsefm.com/2018/07/26/interview-social-house/|title=Interview: Social House|date=2018-07-26|website=WPLW-FM|language=en-US|access-date=2019-01-25}}</ref><ref name=\":8\">{{Cite web|url=https://thepreludepress.com/interviews/2018/7/5/interview-with-social-house|title=Social House Discuss Moving to LA, \"Magic in the Hamptons\" and Plans for New Music: \"There\u2019s Definitely More Magic to Come\"|website=The Prelude Press|language=en-US|access-date=2019-01-25}}</ref> They started out writing and producing songs for other artists, including [[Ariana Grande]],<ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":9\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.refinery29.com/en-us/2018/11/216536/thank-u-next-ariana-grande-social-house-interview|title=\"Thank U, Next\" Would Not Exist Without These 2 Guys (No, Not Exes)|last=Lindsay|first=Kathryn|website=www.refinery29.com|language=en|access-date=2019-01-25}}</ref><ref name=\":0\" /> [[Meghan Trainor]],<ref name=\":7\" /> [[Jennifer Lopez]],<ref name=\":7\" /><ref name=\":6\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ascap.com/repertory#ace/search/title/dinero/performer/jennifer%20lopez|title=ACE Repertory|website=www.ascap.com|access-date=2019-01-25}}</ref> [[Chris Brown|Chris Brown,]]<ref name=\":3\" /> [[Steven Malcolm]]<ref name=\":11\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8483465/social-house-ariana-grande-sweetener-world-tour|title=Social House Joining Ariana Grande on Her Sweetener World Tour|website=Billboard|access-date=2019-01-25}}</ref> and [[NCT 127]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.idolator.com/7751837/nct-127-gma-new-ep-we-are-superhuman|title=NCT 127 Slays 'GMA,' Announces New EP 'WE ARE SUPERHUMAN'|date=2019-05-24|website=idolator|access-date=2019-08-14}}</ref> After their individual careers began to slow down the duo was successfully encouraged by their peers to collaborate on a new music project.<ref name=\":10\">{{Cite web|url=http://stitchedsound.com/social-house-discuss-their-single-magic-in-the-hamptons-working-with-lil-yachty-and-whats-next-for-them/|title=Social House discuss their single \"Magic In The Hamptons\", working with Lil Yachty and what\u2019s next for them|date=2018-10-01|website=Stitched Sound|language=en-US|access-date=2019-01-25}}</ref><ref name=\":5\" /> In 2018, Social House was signed to a joint venture between the labels [[Scooter Braun]], [[Tommy Brown (record producer)|TBHits]], and [[Interscope Records]]. Social House released their debut single \"Magic in the Hamptons\" featuring rapper [[Lil Yachty]] on June 8th, 2018.<ref name=\":6\" /><ref name=\":4\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newsday.com/entertainment/music/social-house-hamptons-1.20109917|title=Social House's 'Magic in the Hamptons' climbing the charts|website=Newsday|language=en|access-date=2019-01-25}}</ref><ref name=\":1\" /> Written about [[The Hamptons]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hotnewhiphop.com/social-house-and-lil-yachty-create-magic-in-the-hamptons-with-new-video-new-video.44482.html|title=Social House & Lil Yachty Create \"Magic In the Hamptons\" With New Video|website=HotNewHipHop|access-date=2019-01-25}}</ref><ref name=\":8\" /> the song has had over seventy million streams on [[Spotify]].<ref name=\":12\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.onestowatch.com/blog/social-house-is-ready-to-take-off-and-go-higher|title=Social House Is Ready to Take Off and Go \"Higher\" Than Ever Before / Ones To Watch|website=Ones To Watch|access-date=2019-01-25}}</ref> On September 28, 2018, their second single, entitled \"Higher\", was released.<ref name=\":9\" /><ref name=\":12\" /> Social House joined Grande\u2019s [[Sweetener World Tour]] in 2019 as an opening act and released \"[[Boyfriend (Ariana Grande and Social House song)|Boyfriend]]\" with her in August 2019.<ref name=\":11\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.msn.com/en-us/music/news/social-house-joining-ariana-grande-on-her-sweetener-world-tour/ar-BBPnD69|title=Social House Joining Ariana Grande on Her Sweetener World Tour|website=MSN|language=en-US|access-date=2019-01-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thepreludepress.com/news/2018/11/6/social-house-to-join-ariana-grande-on-sweetener-world-tour|title=Social House To Join Ariana Grande On Sweetener World Tour|website=The Prelude Press|language=en-US|access-date=2019-01-25}}</ref><ref name=\":9\" />\n\n== Awards and nominations ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Award\n! Category\n! Nominee\n! Result\n! {{abbr|Ref.|References}}\n|-\n|2019\n|[[2019 MTV Video Music Awards]]\n|[[MTV Video Music Award for Song of Summer|Song of Summer]]\n|\"[[Boyfriend (Ariana Grande and Social House song)|Boyfriend]]\"<br>(with [[Ariana Grande]])\n|{{won}}\n| <ref name=\"vmas2019\">{{cite news |last1=Bennett |first1=Anita |title=MTV Video Music Awards \u2013 Complete Winners List |url=https://deadline.com/2019/08/vmas-2019-winners-list-mtv-1202704564/ |accessdate=August 29, 2019 |work=Deadline |date=August 26, 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |2020\n| rowspan=\"2\" |[[62nd Annual Grammy Awards]]\n|[[Grammy Award for Record of the Year|Record of the Year]]\n|\"[[7 Rings]]\"\n|{{nom}}\n| rowspan=\"2\" |<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.grammy.com/grammys/news/2020-grammy-awards-complete-nominees-list|title=2020 GRAMMY Awards: Complete Nominees List|date=2019-11-20|website=GRAMMY.com|language=en|access-date=2019-12-27}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Grammy Award for Best Pop Duo/Group Performance|Best Pop Duo/Group Performance]]\n|\"[[Boyfriend (Ariana Grande and Social House song)|Boyfriend]]\"<br> (with [[Ariana Grande]])\n|{{nom}}\n|}\n\n== Discography ==\n\n===Extended plays===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|+ List of extended plays\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\"| Title\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\"| Details\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=\"2\"| Peak chart positions\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:90%;\"| [[Billboard 200|US]]<br /><ref>{{cite tweet|user=billboardcharts|number=1163461332831789056|title=Debuts on this week's #Billboard200 (2/2)|date=August 19, 2019|accessdate=August 20, 2019}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:90%;\"| [[Canadian Albums Chart|CAN]]<br /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fyimusicnews.ca/articles/2019/08/19/slipknot-has-weeks-no-1-album|title=Slipknot Has This Week's No. 1 Album|website=FYIMusicNews|date=August 19, 2019|accessdate=August 20, 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[Everything Changed...]]''\n|\n* Released: August 9, 2019<ref name=\"billboard-5\">{{cite news |last1=Malach |first1=Hannah |title=Social House: 5 Things to Know About the Ariana Grande Collaborators |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/8525891/social-house-5-things-to-know |accessdate=August 2, 2019 |w